spark session vs spark context | Lec-10



=================================================================
SPARK SESSION vs SPARK CONTEXT - INTERVIEW SUMMARY
=================================================================

Q1: What is SparkContext?
A: Entry point for Spark Core (RDD, accumulators, broadcast variables)
   - Created first in Spark 1.x
   - One per JVM

Q2: What is SparkSession?
A: Unified entry point (Spark 2.0+)
   - Wraps SparkContext + SQLContext + HiveContext
   - One per application

Q3: Key difference?
A: SparkSession includes everything. SparkContext is RDD-only.
   SparkSession can do SQL, streaming, DataFrames. SparkContext cannot.

Q4: Can we use both?
A: spark.sparkContext gives SparkContext from SparkSession

Q5: Which to use for new projects?
A: ONLY SparkSession. SparkContext is legacy now.

=================================================================
REAL-TIME INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=================================================================

Q: Your company has Spark 1.6 code. Moving to Spark 3.x. What changes?

A: Replace:
   # Old Spark 1.6
   conf = SparkConf().setAppName("app")
   sc = SparkContext(conf=conf)
   sqlContext = SQLContext(sc)
   hiveContext = HiveContext(sc)
   
   # New Spark 3.x - ONE line
   spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("app").enableHiveSupport().getOrCreate()

Q: You see code using both sc and spark. Is this valid?

A: Yes. spark = SparkSession.builder.getOrCreate()
   sc = spark.sparkContext  # Valid - gives SparkContext
   # Use spark for DataFrames, sc for RDD operations

Q: How to create SparkSession with custom settings?

A: 
spark = SparkSession.builder \
    .appName("MyApp") \
    .master("yarn") \
    .config("spark.sql.shuffle.partitions", "200") \
    .config("spark.executor.memory", "4g") \
    .enableHiveSupport() \
    .getOrCreate()

Q: What happens if you call getOrCreate() twice?

A: Returns same SparkSession. Singleton pattern. No duplicate.

Q: Real scenario - Legacy job fails because SparkContext stopped. Why?

A: Spark 2.x+ - stopping SparkContext stops SparkSession.
   Fix: Use spark.stop() instead of sc.stop()
   
Q: How to check if SparkContext is active?

A: spark.sparkContext.isStopped  # Returns boolean

Q: What configuration is specific to SparkContext vs SparkSession?

A: SparkContext configs: executor memory, cores, serializer
   SparkSession configs: shuffle partitions, broadcast threshold, dynamic allocation

=================================================================
QUICK COMPARISON TABLE (Memorize)
=================================================================
Feature              | SparkContext | SparkSession
---------------------|--------------|-------------
Introduced in        | Spark 1.x    | Spark 2.0+
RDD Support          | YES          | YES (via sc)
DataFrame/Dataset    | NO           | YES
Spark SQL            | NO           | YES
Hive Support         | NO           | YES (enableHiveSupport)
Streaming            | NO           | YES
Catalyst Optimizer   | NO           | YES
Tungsten Engine      | NO           | YES

=================================================================
CODE TEMPLATE (Interview Ready)
=================================================================
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession

# MODERN WAY (Spark 2.0+)
spark = SparkSession.builder \
    .appName("my_app") \
    .master("local[*]") \
    .config("spark.sql.adaptive.enabled", "true") \
    .getOrCreate()

# Get SparkContext if needed
sc = spark.sparkContext

# Read data
df = spark.read.csv("data.csv")
rdd = sc.textFile("data.txt")

# Clean up
spark.stop()

=================================================================
COMMON INTERVIEW TRICK QUESTION
=================================================================
Q: "I created SparkContext, then SparkSession. Is this correct?"

A: WRONG. SparkSession creates its own SparkContext.
   Creating SparkContext before SparkSession causes error.
   
   # WRONG ❌
   sc = SparkContext()
   spark = SparkSession.builder.getOrCreate()  # ERROR!
   
   # RIGHT ✅
   spark = SparkSession.builder.getOrCreate()
   sc = spark.sparkContext

Q: "How many SparkSessions can run in one JVM?"

A: One active SparkSession per JVM. 
   Multiple sessions possible if previous stopped.
   spark.newSession() creates isolated session for configs.

RULE TO REMEMBER: Spark 2.0+ → USE ONLY SparkSession
                   SparkContext available INSIDE SparkSession
                   Never create SparkContext separately



